e first half of 2018, only China had higher levels of FDI than the United Kingdom; we were in front of the US, Singapore, Hong Kong, Spain and Holland. This is a country in which people are investing now and will invest in future. What are the upsides if we get an agreement with the EU? The foreign exchange has discounted the pound so significantly that we could see a currency bounce. The stock market is falling again today because of the concern about no deal. As a businessperson, I recognise that concern. There is pent up investment in the system of potentially hundreds of billions of pounds, because companies have held back. Fundamentally, I can support this deal because I support the Brexit vote. Being a Scot, I was involved in another referendum. Opposition parties seem unwilling to recognise that the people have spoken. I believe, democratically, in what they have said.     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Giles Watling       Share       Does my hon. Friend agree that yet another referendum would cause greater degrees of pain, uncertainty and delay, when what we need to do is move on?     Share                    The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Colin Clark       Share       My hon. Friend is absolutely right. That is particularly true in Scotland, where the SNP rejected the result of the independence referendum and said that it would call another. We do not need that uncertainty and we do not need our people back at one another’s throats; we need some sort of stability and to be able to move on. Fundamentally, this comes down to good faith. In the words of the Attorney General: “This risk must be weighed against the political and economic imperative on both sides to reach an agreement”. I absolutely agree with that. We should no